Following the first several diagnosed cases of COVID-19 within Washington state, we began tracking the number of confirmed cases and deaths daily based on publicly available information from the Center for Systems Science and Engineering at Johns Hopkins University (Fig. 1
).3 As the number of cases and deaths within Washington State have increased with time along a gradual but exponential scale, similar to trends seen elsewhere in the United States, the number of cases within the University of Washington (UW) Medicine system has also grown (Fig. 2
). Since the University of Washington first started providing information on case numbers on March 10th, the number of confirmed positive COVID-19 cases within the UW Medicine system has increased 1867%, from 6 cases to 118. Similarly, the number of floor and intensive care unit (ICU) beds required for treating these patients has increased, by 120% for floor (from 35 to 77) and 215% for ICU beds (from 13 to 41).

In response to these trends, our division immediately implemented our new vascular surgery COVID-19 guidelines on March 17th (Table I). In the 4 weeks after instituting these changes, the average weekly clinical volume has decreased by 96.5% (43.1 patients to 1.5 per week), with average weekly surgical volume decreasing by 71.7% (from 15 cases to 4.25 per week). Operative cases performed following institution of the guidelines are listed in Table II
. Inpatient consultation volume has also decreased to 1.81 consults per day (47 consults received over 26 days), with 60% being telemedicine “e-consults” in which the patient was never evaluated in-person (Fig. 3
). Of the 47 consultations, 2 involved a confirmed COVID-19 positive patient, while 3 involved a person under investigation (PUI) who later tested negative. Trainee weekly surgical volume has also decreased, by 86.4% (from 12.9 cases/week to 1.75) for the vascular surgery fellow and 84.8% (from 8.2 cases/week to 1.25) for the postgraduate year 3 integrated resident.
